al fascination for filmmakers and viewers. In every decade of Hollywood filmmaking, artists of the screen have fixated upon this fascinating place for its tensions and promises, dazzling illumination and fearsome darkness. The glittering skyscrapers of such films as On the Town have shadowed the characteristic seedy streets in which desperate, passionate stories have played out-as in Scandal Sheet and The Pawnbroker. In other films, the city is a cauldron of bright lights, technology, empire, egotism, fear, hunger, and change--the scenic epitome of America in the modern age. From Street Scene and Breakfast at Tiffany's to Rosemary's Baby, The Warriors, and 25th Hour, the sixteen essays in this book explore the cinematic representation of New York as a city of experience, as a locus of ideographic characters and spaces, as a city of moves and traps, and as a site of allurement and danger. Contributors consider the work of Woody Allen, Blake Edwards, Alfred Hitchcock, Gregory La Cava, Spike Lee, Sidney Lumet, Vincente Minnelli, Roman Polanski, Martin Scorsese, Andy Warhol, and numerous others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Aaron.1 aBukatman, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBukatman, Scott.1 aCarr, Steven Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, Steven Alan.1 aDesser, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesser, David.1 aDixon, Wheeler Winston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Wheeler Winston.1 aFoster, Gwendolyn Audrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Gwendolyn Audrey.1 aGerstner, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGe